Most DeFi protocols make every decision based on one number: the current price.

That's a problem.

A price oracle tells your contract ETH is $2,400. It doesn't tell you whether that's a crash, a recovery, a consolidation, or a pump. For that, you need technical indicators — and until recently, those simply didn't exist on-chain.

This tutorial shows you how to read live RSI, EMA, VWAP, and Bollinger Band values from a Solidity contract using the standard Chainlink AggregatorV3Interface.

Why You Can't Calculate RSI On-Chain

RSI requires 14 periods of historical prices. For daily RSI, that's 14 days of data. For hourly, 14 hours.

Storing and computing this in Solidity would cost thousands in gas per calculation. Floating-point math doesn't exist in EVM. It's not viable.

The practical solution: deliver the pre-calculated value via oracle — the same pattern Chainlink uses for ETH/USD prices.

The Indicators Available On-Chain

Pythia's oracle network delivers pre-calculated technical indicators for 22 tokens across 4 timeframes (1H, 4H, 8H, 1D):



EMA (20, 50, 200 periods)


RSI (14 periods)

VWAP


Bollinger Bands (upper, lower, basis)


Volatility (24H, 7D)

Liquidity

That's 484 live feeds on Polygon mainnet, all using the standard Chainlink AggregatorV3Interface.

Reading the Feed in Solidity

If you've read a Chainlink price feed before, this is identical:

// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity ^0.8.19;

import "@chainlink/contracts/src/v0.8/shared/interfaces/AggregatorV3Interface.sol";

contract IndicatorReader {
 AggregatorV3Interface public rsiFeed;

 // Polygon Amoy testnet: Bitcoin RSI (1D, 14 periods)
 constructor(address _rsiFeedAddress) {
 rsiFeed = AggregatorV3Interface(_rsiFeedAddress);
 }

 function getBitcoinRSI() external view returns (int256) {
 (, int256 rsi, , , ) = rsiFeed.latestRoundData();
 return rsi; // scaled by 1e8 (e.g. 4272000000 = RSI of 42.72)
 }
}

Four lines that return the live RSI for Bitcoin. No API calls, no off-chain computation, no server to maintain.

A Real Use Case: RSI-Aware Liquidations

DeFi lending protocols liquidate positions when collateral drops below a threshold. The problem: many of those liquidations fire during extreme oversold conditions — RSI at 15–20 — where the market typically recovers within hours.

A protocol with access to RSI can avoid unnecessary liquidations during temporary market panics:

// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity ^0.8.19;

import "@chainlink/contracts/src/v0.8/shared/interfaces/AggregatorV3Interface.sol";

contract RSIGatedLending {
 AggregatorV3Interface public priceFeed;
 AggregatorV3Interface public rsiFeed;

 // RSI below this value = extreme oversold (scale: 1e8)
 int256 public constant RSI_OVERSOLD = 25 * 1e8;

 constructor(address _priceFeed, address _rsiFeed) {
 priceFeed = AggregatorV3Interface(_priceFeed);
 rsiFeed = AggregatorV3Interface(_rsiFeed);
 }

 function canLiquidate(address user) external view returns (bool) {
 if (!isUndercollateralized(user)) return false;

 // Delay liquidation when market is at extreme oversold
 (, int256 rsi, , , ) = rsiFeed.latestRoundData();
 if (rsi < RSI_OVERSOLD) {
 // Position is undercollateralized but conditions are extreme oversold
 // Holding off avoids liquidating into a likely temporary flash crash
 return false;
 }

 return true;
 }

 function isUndercollateralized(address user) internal view returns (bool) {
 // Your existing collateral check here
 return false;
 }
}

This doesn't eliminate liquidations. It delays them when RSI indicates market conditions are anomalous — protecting users from getting liquidated during brief panic events.

Another Pattern: EMA Crossover Signal

Many trading strategies use EMA crossovers (when short-term EMA crosses above long-term EMA) as a buy/sell signal. With on-chain EMAs, you can write this logic directly into a contract:

function isEMACrossoverBullish() external view returns (bool) {
 (, int256 ema20, , , ) = ema20Feed.latestRoundData();
 (, int256 ema50, , , ) = ema50Feed.latestRoundData();
 return ema20 > ema50;
}

A vault strategy could use this to dynamically rebalance: deploy more capital when EMAs are bullish, reduce exposure when they're bearish.

